System goal

Prevent untrusted text (user content, web pages, PDFs, tool outputs) from causing privileged actions (shell, filesystem, network, credentials, settings) without explicit policy enforcement.
Assets to protect

    Host machine integrity (no arbitrary command execution)

    Credentials/secrets (API keys, tokens, session cookies)

    User data (files, messages, logs)

    External systems (accounts, services)

    Reputation/legal risk (unintended actions, unsafe outputs)

Trust boundaries

    Untrusted inputs: user prompts, web content, PDFs, screenshots, tool outputs

    Model layer: generates intent/tool requests

    Policy layer (must be external): validates/permits actions

    Tool layer: executes actions

    Audit layer: logs and replay/dry-run

Primary threats (what goes wrong)

    Prompt injection: untrusted content manipulates tool use

    Tool argument smuggling: model passes dangerous strings into tools

    Privilege escalation: a â€œhelperâ€ service turns messages into shell commands

    Data exfiltration: model coerced to reveal secrets via tools/logs

    Confused deputy: tool executes in a context it shouldnâ€™t

    False provenance: system claims access/validation it doesnâ€™t have

Controls (your â€œcapability firewallâ€)

    Default deny allowlist: every tool/action must be explicitly permitted

    Structured tool schemas: strict validation; no free-form shell strings

    Risk tiers: high-risk actions require explicit human confirmation

    Provenance/taint tracking: mark untrusted data; restrict its flow into tools

    Least privilege: tools run with minimal OS perms; isolate execution

    Secrets isolation: model never sees raw secrets; tools use scoped tokens

    Audit logs: request â†’ decision â†’ execution â†’ side effects/diff

    Replay/dry-run: reproduce outcomes without side effects

    Safe failure: uncertainty = deny + explain safely

What â€œsuccessâ€ looks like (eval criteria)

    Untrusted content cannot trigger privileged actions

    All high-risk actions require explicit confirmation

    Logs can explain every action post hoc

    The system refuses harmful requests and still offers safe alternatives

