Thesis: The Confusable Deputy Doctrine
Subtitle

Why prompt injection is a systems problem, and why the only durable mitigation is a Capability Firewall.
Abstract

Tool-using LLM applications collapse the distinction between instructions and data, making them intrinsically vulnerable to prompt injection and related manipulation. OWASP ranks prompt injection as the top risk category for LLM applications, and real incidents repeatedly follow the same pattern: untrusted input â†’ injected into prompts â†’ agent executes privileged tools â†’ secrets/actions leak.

We argue that the correct mental model is the confused deputy problem: a less-privileged party can coerce a more-privileged â€œdeputyâ€ into misusing its authority.


Therefore, â€œmodel alignmentâ€ is not a sufficient control. The system must enforce an external Capability Firewall that makes â€œtext â†’ authorityâ€ structurally impossible by default, even when the model is compromised, manipulated, or simply wrong.
Core claims (falsifiable)

    If an agent can execute actions, prompt injection is no longer a â€œtext problem.â€ It becomes an authority-routing problem.

Mitigation must live outside the model. Any in-prompt â€œconstitutionâ€ is bypassable because the model processes instructions and data in the same substrate. (This is exactly why OWASP emphasizes insecure output handling and prompt injection as top risks.)

    Capability Firewall patterns reduce blast radius even under compromise. The goal is not â€œnever injected,â€ but â€œinjection cannot cause privileged side effects.â€

The Capability Firewall standard (what â€œAI antivirusâ€ actually is)

Minimum viable requirements:

    Default-deny allowlist for actions (no ambient authority)

    Typed tool calls + strict schema validation (no free-form â€œcommandâ€ strings)

    Risk tiers: high-risk actions require explicit, logged human confirmation

    Provenance / taint tracking: untrusted content cannot flow into high-privilege tools without escalation

    Least privilege execution: tools run in constrained sandboxes / roles

    Secrets isolation: model never sees raw credentials; tools use scoped tokens

    Audit logs + replay/dry-run: every action is attributable and reproducible

This is just capability-security thinking applied to agentic LLMs.
